issues and citizen activism on the Moraine's future in the face of rapid urban expansion.The Oak Ridges Moraine Battles captures the hidden aspects of a story that received a great deal of attention in the local and national news, and that ultimately led to provincial legislation aimed at protecting the Moraine and Ontario's Greenbelt. By giving voice to a range of actors - residents, activists, civil servants, scientists, developers and aggregate and other resource users, the book demonstrates how space on the urban periphery was reshaped in the Toronto region. The authors ask hard questions about who is included and excluded when the preservation of nature challenges the relentless process of urbanization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aNature conservationxCitizen participationxOntarioxOak Ridges Moraine. 0aNature conservationxOntarioxToronto Region. 0aNature conservationxPlanningxOntarioxOak Ridges Moraine. 0aNature conservationzOntarioxCitizen participationxOak Ridges Moraine. 0aNature conservationzOntarioxPlanningxOak Ridges Moraine. 0aNature conservationzOntarioxToronto Region. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aGilbert, Liette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWekerle, Gerda R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266652840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442666528423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442666528.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  